<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-617-801  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 617 801.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Oct 29 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Australian financial watch-dog uses Macs to monitor transactions.andO;(the Cash Transaction Reports Agency uses Apple Macintoshcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McNamara, Sean.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Australia. Cash Transaction Reports AgencyNetwork MonitorsGovernment RegulationAustraliaNetwork Management Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AUSTRALIAN FINANCIAL WATCH-DOG USES MACS TO MONITOR TRANSACTIONS SYDNEY,AUSTRALIA, 1990 OCT 26 (NB) -- The Australian Federal government's newfinancial watch-dog, the Cash Transaction Reports Agency (CTRA), ismonitoring transactions for shady deals with over forty Macintoshes networkedto a Tandem mainframe.andM;The CTRA was set up last year to detect possible law infringements inmonetary dealings.andP;  Any cash transaction over AUS$10,00 has to be reported,as well as any dealing felt by the financial institution to be suspicious.andO;It is expected that up to AUS$100M per year in (previously) lost revenue willbe collected under the new system.andM;Currently, the CTRA is monitoring around 2 million transactions a year, andgovernment agencies which have access to this information include theAustralian Taxation Office, Customs, Federal Police, the National CrimeAuthority, state police, and the New South Wales State Drug Crime Commission.andO;According to Max Montanaro, head of Information Technology at the CTRA, &quot;Inthe US equivalent there is a delay of about 45 days between the time thetransaction is noticed and when it is on the system.andP;  We expect to cut thisdelay to a week, and eventually to 48 hours.&quot; As a security feature, thecomputers on the network have had their disk drives disabled to prevent virusattacks and the loading of programs for illegally accessing the server.andM;(Sean McNamara/19901029/Press Contact: Nick Verykios, phone in Australia+61-2-888 5533)</TEXT></DOC>